{
  "doc_id": "39858",
  "text": "The exact histiogenesis of GCT lesions remains uncertain, but immunohistochemical studies identifying the presence of S-100 protein and neuron-specific enolase support a neural cell origin theory, with GCT likely originating from Schwann cells. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] GCT are generally benign tumors, and often remain stable or very slowly increase in size. [CITATION_3] Malignancy is rare, occurring in less than 1-2% of lesions. [CITATION_4] Management includes monitoring the lesion for stability or resection. However, as these lesions are submucosal, there is a potentially increased risk of perforation with removal. [CITATION_5] Although some physicians may prefer surveillance rather than resection, there is no consensus on the appropriate interval to survey. If completely resected, recurrence is unlikely. However, patients should be followed up after resection, as there is a 2-10% risk of recurrence. [CITATION_6] Multifocal lesions, either synchronous or metachronous, are distinctly uncommon. [CITATION_7] Fried et al reported a case with multiple synchronous gastrointestinal GCT of the esophagus, stomach, appendix, and cecum. [CITATION_8] In a study of 74 cases of GCT of the GI tract and perianal region, only 3 of 74 patients had multiplicity of tumors; only one case showed involvement in more than one segment of the GI tract. [CITATION_9] If multiple lesions are found, they are typically grouped in one area, especially the esophagus or stomach. [CITATION_10] The occurrence of multiple lesions does not appear to increase the risk of malignancy. [CITATION_11] None of our patient's 7 tumors were malignant.",
